{{orphan|date=March 2012}}
'''Goeckerman therapy''' is a regimen for treatment of moderate to severe [[plaque psoriasis]] using a combination of crude [[coal tar]] and artificial [[ultraviolet radiation]]. It is a specialized form of [[light therapy]].
First formulated in 1925 by American dermatologist William H. Goeckerman (1884–1954), Goeckerman therapy continues to be used due to its [[efficacy]] and [[safety profile]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Goeckerman|first1=W. H.|title=The treatment of psoriasis|journal=Northwest Med|date=1925|volume=24|pages=229–231}}</ref> Individual institutions have modified the Goeckerman regimen and developed their own protocols. Standard therapy includes use of 2–4% crude [[coal tar]] in a [[petroleum]] base applied daily to the [[plaque (dermatology)|psoriatic plaques]]. The minimum period of time for tar application is 2-hours, although it has been recognized that greater periods of time produce better results.<ref name="PMID6886105">{{cite journal|last1=Menter|first1=Alan|last2=Cram|first2=David L.|title=The Goeckerman regimen in two psoriasis day care centers|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Dermatology|date=July 1983|volume=9|issue=1|pages=59–65|doi=10.1016/S0190-9622(83)70107-6|pmid=6886105}}</ref> The patient is then exposed to broad-band ultraviolet B ([[UVB]]) radiation, although narrow-band [[UVB]] may also be used.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lee|first1=E.|last2=Koo|first2=J.|title=Modern modified ‘ultra’ Goeckerman therapy: A PASI assessment of a very effective therapy for psoriasis resistant to both prebiologic and biologic therapies|journal=Journal of Dermatological Treatment|date=12 July 2009|volume=16|issue=2|pages=102–107|doi=10.1080/09546630510033140|pmid=16019624}}</ref> Laboratory studies have shown that the combination of [[coal tar]] and [[UV light]] reduces epidermal [[DNA synthesis]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bolognia|first1=J L|last2=Rapini|first2=R|last3=Jorizzo|first3=J L|title=Dermatology|date=2003|publisher=Mosby|location=London|isbn=9780323025782}}</ref>
==Modifications== [[File:William H. Goeckerman, MD.jpg|Headstone of William H. Goeckerman|thumb|right]] In 1953, John Ingram, an English dermatologist, added topical [[anthralin]] paste to his Goeckerman regimen. This is known as the Ingram method.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ingram|first1=JT|title=The approach to psoriasis.|journal=British Medical Journal|date=12 September 1953|volume=2|issue=4836|pages=591–4|pmc=2029626|doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4836.591|pmid=13082048}}</ref>
==Cost== Recent publications have compared Goeckerman therapy with treatment with more expensive [[biologic agent]]s.<ref name="PMID19538381">{{cite journal|last1=de Miguel|first1=Rebeca|last2=el-Azhary|first2=Rokea|title=Efficacy, safety, and cost of Goeckerman therapy compared with biologics in the treatment of moderate to severe psoriasis|journal=International Journal of Dermatology|date=June 2009|volume=48|issue=6|pages=653–658|doi=10.1111/j.1365-4632.2009.04012.x|pmid=19538381}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dennis|first1=Madison|last2=Bhutani|first2=Tina|last3=Koo|first3=John|last4=Liao|first4=Wilson|title=Goeckerman therapy for the treatment of eczema: a practical guide and review of efficacy|journal=Journal of Dermatological Treatment|date=24 August 2011|volume=24|issue=1|pages=2–6|doi=10.3109/09546634.2011.607794|pmid=21797807|pmc=3678985}}</ref> Historically, Goeckerman therapy was performed as an [[inpatient]] treatment. However, today the treatment can be done with reduced cost as an [[outpatient]]. It has been stated by de Miguel et al., that an annual three-week [[outpatient]] course of Goeckerman treatment costs $10,000 to 12,000 but repeat treatment may be extended to two years with the use of a $2,000 home [[uvb lamps|UVB treatment lamp]].<ref name="PMID19538381" /> The authors state that [[biologic therapy]] costs $22,000 to 59,000 per year.
==Safety== Goeckerman regimens use crude [[coal tar]], which contains [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]], a [[carcinogen]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Boström|first1=CE|last2=Gerde|first2=P|last3=Hanberg|first3=A|last4=Jernström|first4=B|last5=Johansson|first5=C|last6=Kyrklund|first6=T|last7=Rannug|first7=A|last8=Törnqvist|first8=M|last9=Victorin|first9=K|last10=Westerholm|first10=R|title=Cancer risk assessment, indicators, and guidelines for polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons in the ambient air.|journal=Environmental Health Perspectives|date=June 2002|volume=110 Suppl 3|pages=451–88|pmc=1241197|doi=10.1289/ehp.02110s3451|pmid=12060843}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Borska|first1=Lenka|last2=Andrys|first2=Ctirad|last3=Krejsek|first3=Jan|last4=Hamakova|first4=Kvetoslava|last5=Kremlacek|first5=Jan|last6=Palicka|first6=Vladimir|last7=Ranna|first7=Dianna|last8=Fiala|first8=Zdenek|title=Genotoxic and apoptotic effects of Goeckerman therapy for psoriasis|journal=International Journal of Dermatology|date=March 2010|volume=49|issue=3|pages=289–294|doi=10.1111/j.1365-4632.2009.04258.x|pmid=20465666}}</ref> However, Goeckerman therapy is considered safe although use of tar may have the side-effects of [[contact dermatitis]] and mild local burning due to tar [[hypersensitivity]]. A retrospective study by Stern et al., of 1,373 patients concluded that there was an increase in [[skin cancer]]s in those receiving repeated Goeckerman treatments compared to the [[control group]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stern|first1=RobertS.|last2=Zierler|first2=Sally|last3=Parrish|first3=JohnA.|title=Skin carcinoma in patients with psoriasis treated with topical tar and artificial ultraviolet radiation|journal=The Lancet|date=April 1980|volume=315|issue=8171|pages=732–735|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(80)91231-3|pmid=6103156}}</ref> This has been refuted by other authors, including Pittelkow et al., who state there has not been an increase in [[skin cancer]]s among those treated compared to the general population<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pittelkow|first1=Mark R.|title=Skin Cancer in Patients With Psoriasis Treated With Coal Tar|journal=Archives of Dermatology|date=1 August 1981|volume=117|issue=8|pages=465–8|doi=10.1001/archderm.1981.01650080019020|pmid=7259240}}</ref> and Menter and Cran, who felt that the Stern study was too crude to have validity and felt a 10-year prospective study would be needed to confirm safety concerns.<ref name="PMID6886105" />
==Efficacy== With the increased use of biologic medications in treatment of moderate-to-severe [[psoriasis]] there has been a shift away from Goeckerman therapy. A 2007 comparative study of psoriasis treatment found Goeckerman therapy to be more efficacious at 12-weeks than biologics.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leon|first1=Argentina|last2=Nguyen|first2=Alain|last3=Letsinger|first3=Julie|last4=Koo|first4=John|title=An attempt to formulate an evidence-based strategy in the management of moderate-to-severe psoriasis: a review of the efficacy and safety of biologics and prebiologic options|journal=Expert Opinion on Pharmacotherapy|date=22 March 2007|volume=8|issue=5|pages=617–632|doi=10.1517/14656566.8.5.617|pmid=17376017}}</ref> It has also been successfully used in patients who have failed some biologic therapies.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Serrao|first1=Rocco|last2=Davis|first2=Mark D.P.|title=Goeckerman treatment for remission of psoriasis refractory to biologic therapy|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Dermatology|date=February 2009|volume=60|issue=2|pages=348–349|doi=10.1016/j.jaad.2008.10.016|pmid=19150284}}</ref>
