{{about|the Australian political party and lobby group|the New Zealand lobby group|Grey Power (New Zealand)|the World Curling Tour event|Players' Championships}}
'''Grey Power''' was an [[Australian]] political party and lobby group, first registered in 1983. At the federal elections of [[Australian federal election, 1984|1984]] and [[Australian federal election, 1987|1987]] it ran candidates, but on both occasions these candidates (who included former Liberal cabinet minister [[William Wentworth (Australian politician)|Bill Wentworth]]) did poorly. The group was designed to represent the elderly vote, advocating issues dealing with aged care and a mature perspective on national policy; hence the name "grey power".
Grey Power ran in the [[Western Australian state election, 1989|1989 Western Australian state election]], garnering 5.2% of the total lower house vote. The last election which Grey Power contested was the [[South Australian state election, 1997|1997 South Australian state election]], but then it only managed to receive 1.6% of the [[South Australian Legislative Council]] vote. Their preferences however significantly contributed to the election of [[Nick Xenophon]].
The best result Grey Power ever achieved was at the [[Taylor state by-election, 1994|1994 Taylor state by-election]] in South Australia. Without a Liberal candidate in the running on this occasion, Grey Power took 13 percent of the primary vote and finished second after preferences had been distributed with a 27 percent [[Two-party-preferred vote|two-candidate preferred vote]].
